Sammy the Seal is selling his fresh takeaway! He has created a `Fish` class and a `TakeawayBox` class to store any type of takeaway food. Here's the code:

```java
class Food {
}
class Meat extends Food {
}
class Fish extends Food {
}
class Salmon extends Fish {
}
class TakeawayBox<T extends Food> {
    private T fish;
    public void setFish(T fish) {
        this.fish = fish;
    }
    public T getFish() {
        return fish;
    }
}
class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        TakeawayBox<???> box = new TakeawayBox<>();
    }
}
```

What should replace the `???` in the `TakeawayBox` declaration to ensure it only accepts objects of the `Fish` type or its `subclasses` (like `Salmon`)?

Take a look at the following code snippet:

```java
class MarineAnimal {
    public static void displaySpecies() throws NoSuchMethodException {
        throw new NoSuchMethodException("MarineAnimal: displaySpecies");
    }
}

class Seal extends MarineAnimal {
    public static void displaySpecies() throws NoSuchMethodException {
        throw new RuntimeException("Seal: displaySpecies");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Seal marine1 = new Seal();
        try {
            marine1.displaySpecies();
        } catch (NoSuchMethodException e) {
            System.out.println("MarineAnimal: no such method");
        }
    }
}
```

What will be the output of this code?
